<td valign="top">

<center><table width="96%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><col width="64"><col width="15"><tr><td bgcolor="f0f0f0f" background="25pxheading.gif" align="center" height="25"><font face="arial" color="000000" size="3"><b>The Matrix: Reloaded </b></font></td></tr><tr><td align="center"> <font size="2" face="arial">Posted By <a href="mailto:sean@data-zoid.com">Sean</a> on Thursday 15th May, 2003 @ 20:42 (Read: 344) &nbsp;<a href="printnews.php?id=61"><img src="http://www.data-zoid.com/brutallyhonest/images/print.gif" border="0" Alt="Printable Version"></a></font></td></tr><tr><td width="93%" valign="top"><div><br><font size="2" face="arial">
<a href="searchcat.php?cid=2">
<img src="http://www.data-zoid.com/brutallyhonest/images/category/" border="0" align="right" hspace="10" vspace="10" alt="">
</a>

<img src="http://www.thematrix-fr.com/x_poster_laurence_full.jpg" align="left"> 

<table width="250">
<tr>
<td bgcolor="#F8F3D7">
<font size="2" face="arial">IMDB: <a href="" target="new"></a><br>
Buy this here: <a href="" target="new">Buy!</a><BR></font>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<br>
<font size="2" face="arial"> :| @ Pie<br><br>It has been four years since the Matrix came out, alluding to everything in site, the quintessential movie where you know someone actually went, "If I made an action movie, this is how it would be," and went ahead and did it. Actually, it was two somebodies, and it was not so high on my list of movies I liked for awhile, until I saw it multiple times.<br />
<br />
I fear the same here. The movie is good. I will give it that. But I know already the "professionals" are breaking out with their patented cynicism usually reserved for George Lucas, and should be hammering away at the movie now. Why? Because they are stupid.<br />
<br />
No, I'm not saying that in the childish, "You don't like what I like so you suck" way. I'm saying it because it is quite obvious the only people who would bother to get hyped up on the Matrix enough to be disappointed by this film weren't looking at it correctly.<br />
<br />
Here is why they would be disappointed, and you may be too:<br />
<br />
1) Keanu Reeves is a horrid actor.<br />
2) One or two fight scenes, while amusing and badass, seem rather pointless, other than for the point for some guy to throw a nice one liner.<br />
3) The movie makes allusions, biblical, literary, historical -- left and right. And it doesn't do what you want it to do.<br />
4) Neo, while much into the ass kicking, is not going to just go around randomly fucking people up.<br />
5) The sequences are refined. Very refined. Too refined. By the time you see them, they don't feel so new and groundbreaking. (Although if you follow through and DO NOT watch any trailers for this film, you will be suitably astonished.)<br />
6) The movie alludes to its predacessor. I'd have called it downright copying, except for the fact that its single purpose seems to be to tear down much of what you learned and saw in the first movie. And any time you have a love relationship on screen, expecially involving Reeves, you're going to wind up with corny moments.<br />
7) This movie answers questions. It also raises others, but they aren't happy. The answered questions raise a more complex mystery, one which doesn't have the immediate mental gratification and "whoa-factor."<br />
8) This movie is a cliffhanger. Predictable as this is, it ends in a way that leaves you going, "Okay, things are different, the main characters have no clue what to do next, they have short time, and they better not eat any pie."<br />
<br />
Again, allow me to reiterate. If you are in the Matrix, beware pie. (Or was it chocolate cake? Better keep away from all deserts altogether.) The scene I am referencing is downright... weird.<br />
<br />
Perhaps though, it isn't nearly as weird as the whole "dance scene" thrown into the movie. At first when I saw it, I was thinking, "Wow.. time filler..." But as it began to drag along, I realized, "Hey, this scene has meaning." The meaning is of course a contrast of the nature of biological organisms, frought with desire, passion, and an apreciation for a good beat... Still, this and a couple other sequences run long.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now for why I liked this movie. <br />
<br />
First of, Datazoi... Hugo Weaving manages to pass himself off as more malevolent than ever, and actually busts out with a couple laugh-inspiring moments.<br />
<br />
The movie deserves a second viewing,  with the search for a ground-breaking new fight sequence removed. (The car sequence did come close.) The plot via the nature of the Matrix is a mental thing.<br />
<br />
Short version:<br />
Hugo Rocks, Keanu needs acting lessons. Morpheus shouldn't make speeches, and neither should I. Watch it once, watch it twice, don't let your expectations fool you, and you'll love this movie. Don't let the ripoffs/allusions annoy/confuse you, and you'll think it is "badass." If you're looking for entirely new, then don't watch a sequel.<br />
 <br />
PS -- Chris probably hated this movie.</font></div>
</tr>
</div>
